    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#marengo2010a"/>, pp. 152-153, n. <citedRange>19</citedRange>, fig. 4, 19</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>112700</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><space extent="unknown" unit="character"/><orig>τω</orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                </ab></div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
                <p>Intraduisible.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
                <p>Intraducibile.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>غير قابل للترجمة بشكل جيد</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Perhaps <foreign xml:lang="grc">τὠπόλλωνι</foreign> or <foreign xml:lang="grc">τὠπόλλωνος</foreign>, but this remains very uncertain,
                    the more so that such dedications of vases were found in Apollo's sanctuary rather than on the agora.</p>
                <p>The dating of the ceramics being the last quarter of the fifth century, the graffito might be somewhat later and would offer one of the
                earliest instances of omega, thus giving a clue for the adoption of the standard alphabet.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
